\[\sum_{k = 1}^\infty \frac{k + 2}{k! + (k+1)! + (k+2)!}\]

First, we can simplify the denominator by factoring out $(k+2)!$:

\[\sum_{k = 1}^\infty \frac{k + 2}{(k+2)! \left( \frac{1}{(k+2)!} + \frac{k+1}{(k+2)!} + 1 \right)}\]

This simplifies to:

\[\sum_{k = 1}^\infty \frac{k + 2}{(k+2)! \left( \frac{k+2 + (k+2)!}{(k+2)!} \right)}\]

Which further simplifies to:

\[\sum_{k = 1}^\infty \frac{k+2}{(k+2 + (k+2)!)}\]

Now, notice a pattern emerges when we write out the first few terms:

\begin{align*}
S_n &= \sum_{k=1}^n \frac{k+2}{(k+2 + (k+2)!)} \\
&= \frac{3}{3 + 3!} + \frac{4}{4 + 4!} + \frac{5}{5 + 5!} + \dots + \frac{n+2}{n+2 + (n+2)!}
\end{align*}

Each term can be expressed as:

\begin{align*}
\frac{k+2}{k+2 + (k+2)!} &= \frac{1}{1 + \frac{(k+2)!}{k+2}} \\
&= \frac{1}{1 + (k+1)!} - \frac{1}{1 + k!}
\end{align*}

This creates a telescoping series where most of the terms cancel out:

\begin{align*}
S_n &= \left( \frac{1}{1 + 2!} - \frac{1}{1 + 1!} \right) + \left( \frac{1}{1 + 3!} - \frac{1}{1 + 2!} \right) + \left( \frac{1}{1 + 4!} - \frac{1}{1 + 3!} \right) + \dots + \left( \frac{1}{1 + (n+2)!} - \frac{1}{1 + (n+1)!} \right) \\
&= \frac{1}{1 + (n+2)!} - \frac{1}{1 + 1!} \\
&= \frac{1}{1 + (n+2)!} - 1
\end{align*}

Finally, as $n$ approaches infinity, the term $\frac{1}{1 + (n+2)!}$ approaches 0.  Therefore,

\[\lim_{n \to \infty} S_n = \boxed{-1}.\]

